By no means are these questions new: They have been debated since well before the internment of Japanese American citizens during World War II.
What is different in Muthana’s case is that the government has, in effect, retroactively stripped her of recognition as a citizen.
Immigrants have prized American citizenship because, among other things, it accords their U.S.-born children the same rights and opportunities as other native-born Americans.
Muthana’s case illustrates how illusory those protections could be.
His teenage son, also an American citizen, was killed two weeks later in another strike.